\section{[[hellorio.ml]]}

%claude:
Before diving into [[rio]] itself, I will present a toy graphical
application called [[hellorio]]. It draws a line that follows the
mouse cursor, and prints typed characters. Despite its simplicity,
it introduces the key concepts used throughout [[rio]]: display
initialization, mouse and keyboard handling, and the event loop
with [[Event.select]].

<<constant [[Hellorio._]]>>=
let _ =
  Cap.main (fun caps -> thread_main caps)
@

%claude:
The main function takes a capability object listing everything the
program needs: display access, keyboard, mouse, and file reading
(for [[/dev/winname]]). This makes resource dependencies visible
in the type signature rather than hidden in global state.
%claude:
The initialization follows a standard pattern: connect to the
display with [[Draw.init]], obtain the window image with
[[Draw_rio.get_view]], then set up input devices.
[[Keyboard.init]] and [[Mouse.init]] each spawn a background
thread that reads from the real [[/dev/cons]] and [[/dev/mouse]]
and forwards events through channels.

<<function [[Hellorio.thread_main]]>>=
(* the Keyboard.init() and Mouse.init() below create other threads *)
let thread_main (caps : < Cap.draw; Cap.open_in; Cap.keyboard; Cap.mouse; .. >) =
  let display : Display.t = Draw.init caps "Hello Rio" in
  let view : Display.image = Draw_rio.get_view caps display in

  let kbd : Keyboard.ctl = Keyboard.init caps in
  let mouse : Mouse.ctl = Mouse.init caps in

  let bgcolor : Image.t  = 
    Image.alloc display Rectangle.r_1x1 Channel.rgba32 true Color.magenta
  in
  (* if does not use originwindow, then need to add view.r.min *)
  let mousepos = ref (Point.add view.r.Rectangle.min (Point.p 10 10)) in

  redraw display view !mousepos bgcolor;

  while true do
    <<[[Hellorio.thread_main()]] in event loop>>
    redraw display view !mousepos bgcolor;
  done
@
% keyboard.init will turn rawon on /dev/consctl

<<function [[Hellorio.redraw]]>>=
let redraw (display : Display.t) (view : Display.image) (pos : Point.t)
     (bgcolor : Image.t) : unit =
  Draw.draw view view.r bgcolor None Point.zero;
  (* todo: Text.string *)
  Line.line view pos (Point.add pos (Point.p 100 100))
    Line.EndSquare Line.EndSquare 2 display.black Point.zero;
  Display.flush display
@
%ocaml: less globals, pass down view and display

%claude:
The event type is a simple sum type---the OCaml equivalent
of a tagged union. Each branch wraps the payload from the
corresponding input device.

<<type [[Hellorio.event]]>>=
type event =
  | Mouse of Mouse.state
  | Key of Keyboard.key
  (* less: Resize *)
@

%claude:
The event loop uses [[Event.select]] to wait on multiple channels
simultaneously: whichever channel has data ready first wins.
This is the OCaml equivalent of Plan~9's [[alt()]] or Go's
[[select]] statement. Each channel is wrapped with [[Event.wrap]]
to tag the payload into the [[event]] sum type.

<<[[Hellorio.thread_main()]] in event loop>>=
let ev : event = 
  [
    Keyboard.receive kbd |> (fun ev -> Event.wrap ev (fun x -> Key x));
    Mouse.receive mouse |> (fun ev -> Event.wrap ev (fun x -> Mouse x));
  ] |> Event.select
in
(match ev with
| Mouse m -> 
  mousepos := m.pos
| Key c ->
  if c = 'q'
  then exit 0
  else Logs.app (fun m -> m "%c" c)
(* less: 
 * | Resize -> view := getwindow display
 *)
);
@
% both receive, but can also select on send! so whatever ready to
% receive or send!


