%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Core Data Structures}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:core-ds}

%claude:
In this chapter, I will present the core data structures of [[rio]].
The most important one is [[Window.t]], the central record type
that groups together everything about a window: its graphics, input
channels, process information, and text buffer.

\section{Device handles}

%claude:
A graphical application under \plan needs three things: a display
connection for output, and mouse and keyboard handles for input.
In this OCaml version, these are not globals---they are local
bindings created in [[thread_main]] and passed to the threads
that need them.

\subsection{Output device: [[display]] and [[view]]}
%ocaml: not globals anymore, passed down functions

\subsection{Input devices: [[mouse]] and [[kbd]]}%%[[mousectl]] and [[keyboardctl]]}
%ocaml: also not globals anymore! threads can be passed arguments!

\section{Desktop}%%, [[desktop]]}
%ocaml: also not a global anymore

%claude:
The desktop is a [[Baselayer.t]], a screen on top of [[view]]
that supports overlapping layers. Every window will be allocated
as a layer on this desktop, which handles z-ordering and
repainting of overlapping regions automatically.

\section{Windows}
\label{sec:core-ds-Windows}

\subsection{[[Window.t]]}

%claude:
[[Window.t]] is the central data structure of [[rio]], grouping
together everything about a window: its identity, its graphics
surface, channels for receiving mouse and keyboard events, a link
to the external process running in the window, and the text buffer
for terminal emulation. The fields are organized into ten categories,
presented gradually throughout the book.

<<type [[Window.t]]>>=
(* The window type! *)
type t = {
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* ID *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] id fields>>

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Graphics *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] graphics fields>>

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Mouse *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] mouse fields>>

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Keyboard *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] keyboard fields>>

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Commands *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] command fields>>

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Process *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] process fields>>

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Config *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] config fields>>

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Wm *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] wm fields>>

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Textual Window *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] textual window fields>>

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Graphical Window *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] graphical window fields>>

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Concurrency *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* less: 
   * - a Ref (Mutex.t? atomic anyway in ocaml), ref counting
   *   or simply a counter as there is no race issue for rio-ocaml.
   * - Qlock (Condition.t?), needed for?
   *)

  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  (* Misc *)
  (* ---------------------------------------------------------------- *)
  <<[[Window.t]] other fields>>
}
@

<<type [[Window.wid]]>>=
(* window id *)
type wid = int
@


<<[[Window.t]] id fields>>=
(* visible in /mnt/wsys/winid (and used for /mnt/wsys/<id>/devs) *)
id: wid;
@
