%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Conclusion}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:conclusion}

%claude:
You now know how the \plan windowing system [[rio]] works,
at least for the core architecture and the parts ported to OCaml
so far.

%claude:
The key insight is [[rio]]'s triple nature: it is simultaneously
a graphical application (using the display and input devices),
a filesystem server (speaking 9P over a pipe to provide virtual
[[/dev/cons]] and [[/dev/mouse]] to its clients), and a concurrent
program (with dedicated threads for the keyboard, the mouse, each
window, and the filesystem server, all communicating through channels).

%claude:
The channel-of-channels pattern, where the window thread's
[[Event.select]] includes conditional [[Event.send]] entries to
offer data to filesystem worker threads, is perhaps the most
elegant concurrency pattern in the code. It allows the window
thread to act as both a consumer (of keyboard and mouse events)
and a producer (of data for [[/dev/mouse]] and [[/dev/cons]]
readers) within a single event loop.

%claude:
For the full details of the textual window (terminal emulation,
frame rendering, scrolling, text editing) and the many advanced
features (snarf/paste, plumbing, auto-complete, recursive [[rio]]),
see the C version in \book{Windows}.

